I81Rule 1. Scope

I11(a) T4Cases Involving a Petition underK 28 T4U.S.C.K ÿ1A2254. These rules govern a petition for a writ of habeas corpus filed in a United States district court under 28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2254 by:

I12(1) a person in custody under a state-court judgment who seeks a determination that the custody violates the Constitution, laws, or treaties of the United States; and

I12(2) a person in custody under a state-court or federal-court judgment who seeks a determination that future custody under a state-court judgment would violate the Constitution, laws, or treaties of the United States.

Q04

I11(b) T4Other CasesK. The district court may apply any or all of these rules to a habeas corpus petition not covered by Rule 1(a).

I53(As amended Apr. 26, 2004, eff. Dec. 1, 2004.)

I74Advisory Committee Note

I21Rule 1 provides that the habeas corpus rules are applicable to petitions by persons in custody pursuant to a judgment of a state court. See T3Preiser v. RodriguezK, 411 U.S. 475, 484 (1973). Whether the rules ought to apply to other situations (T3e.gK., person in active military service, T3Glazier v. HackelK, 440 F.2d 592 (9th Cir. 1971); or a reservist called to active duty but not reported, T3Hammond v. LenfestK, 398 F.2d 705 (2d Cir. 1968)) is left to the discretion of the court.

I21The basic scope of habeas corpus is prescribed by statute. 28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2241(c) provides that the ``writ of habeas corpus shall not extend to a prisoner unless***(h)e is T3in custodyK in violation of the Constitution.'' 28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2254 deals specifically with state custody, providing that habeas corpus shall apply only ``in behalf of a person in custody pursuant to a judgment of a state court***.''

I21In T3Preiser v. Rodriguez, supraK, the court said: ``It is clear ... that the essence of habeas corpus is an attack by a person in custody upon the legality of that custody, and that the traditional function of the writ is to secure release from illegal custody.'' 411 U.S. at 484.

I21Initially the Supreme Court held that habeas corpus was appropriate only in those situations in which petitioner's claim would, if upheld, result in an immediate release from a present custody. T3McNally v. HillK, 293 U.S. 131 (1934). This was changed in T3Peyton v. RoweK, 391 U.S. 54 (1968), in which the court held that habeas corpus was a proper way to attack a consecutive sentence to be served in the future, expressing the view that consecutive sentences resulted in present custody under both judgments, not merely the one imposing the first sentence. This view was expanded in T3Carafas v. LaValleeK, 391 U.S. 234 (1968), to recognize the propriety of habeas corpus in a case in which petitioner was in custody when the petition had been originally filed but had since been unconditionally released from custody.

I21See also T3Preiser v. RodriguezK, 411 U.S. at 486 et seq.

I21Since T3CarafasK, custody has been construed more liberally by the courts so as to make a ÿ1A2255 motion or habeas corpus petition proper in more situations. ``In custody'' now includes a person who is: on parole, T3Jones v. CunninghamK, 371 U.S. 236 (1963); at large on his own recognizance but subject to several conditions pending execution of his sentence, T3Hensley v. Municipal CourtK, 411 U.S. 345 (1973); or released on bail after conviction pending final disposition of his case, T3Lefkowitz v. NewsomeK, 95 S.Ct. 886 (1975). See also T3United States v. ReK, 372 F.2d 641 (2d Cir.), cert. denied, 388 U.S. 912 (1967) (on probation); T3Walker v. North CarolinaK, 262 F.Supp. 102 (W.D.N.C. 1966), aff'd per curiam, 372 F.2d 129 (4th Cir.), cert. denied, 388 U.S. 917 (1967) (recipient of a conditionally suspended sentence); T3Burris v. RyanK, 397 F.2d 553 (7th Cir. 1968); T3Marden v. PurdyK, 409 F.2d 784 (5th Cir. 1969) (free on bail); T3United States ex rel. Smith v. DibellaK, 314 F.Supp. 446 (D.Conn. 1970) (release on own recognizance); T3Choung v. CaliforniaK, 320 F.Supp. 625 (E.D.Cal. 1970) (federal stay of state court sentence); T3United States ex rel. Meadows v. New YorkK, 426 F.2d 1176 (2d Cir. 1970), cert. denied, 401 U.S. 941 (1971) (subject to parole detainer warrant); T3Capler v. City of GreenvilleK, 422 F.2d 299 (5th Cir. 1970) (released on appeal bond); T3Glover v. North CarolinaK, 301 F.Supp. 364 (E.D.N.C. 1969) (sentence served, but as convicted felon disqualified from engaging in several activities).

I21The courts are not unanimous in dealing with the above situations, and the boundaries of custody remain somewhat unclear. In T3Morgan v. ThomasK, 321 F.Supp. 565 (S.D.Miss. 1970), the court noted:

I22It is axiomatic that actual physical custody or restraint is not required to confer habeas jurisdiction. Rather, the term is synonymous with restraint of liberty. The real question is how much restraint of one's liberty is necessary before the right to apply for the writ comes into play. ***

I22It is clear however, that something more than moral restraint is necessary to make a case for habeas corpus.

I71321 F.Supp. at 573

I21T3Hammond v. LenfestK, 398 F.2d 705 (2d Cir. 1968), reviewed prior ``custody'' doctrine and reaffirmed a generalized flexible approach to the issue. In speaking about 28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2241, the first section in the habeas corpus statutes, the court said:

I22While the language of the Act indicates that a writ of habeas corpus is appropriate only when a petitioner is ``in custody,'' *** the Act ``does not attempt to mark the boundaries of `custody' nor in any way other than by use of that word attempt to limit the situations in which the writ can be used.'' *** And, recent Supreme Court decisions have made clear that ``[i]t [habeas corpus] is not now and never has been a static, narrow, formalistic remedy; its scope has grown to achieve its grand purpose_the protection of individuals against erosion of their right to be free from wrongful restraints upon their liberty.'' *** ``[B]esides physical imprisonment, there are other restraints on a man's liberty, restraints not shared by the public generally, which have been thought sufficient in the English-speaking world to support the issuance of habeas corpus.''

I71398 F.2d at 710ÿ09711

I21There is, as of now, no final list of the situations which are appropriate for habeas corpus relief. It is not the intent of these rules or notes to define or limit ``custody.''

I21It is, however, the view of the Advisory Committee that claims of improper conditions of custody or confinement (not related to the propriety of the custody itself), can better be handled by other means such as 42 U.S.C. ÿ1A1983 and other related statutes. In T3Wilwording v. SwansonK, 404 U.S. 249 (1971), the court treated a habeas corpus petition by a state prisoner challenging the conditions of confinement as a claim for relief under 42 U.S.C. ÿ1A1983, the Civil Rights Act. Compare T3Johnson v. AveryK, 393 U.S. 483 (1969).

I21The distinction between duration of confinement and conditions of confinement may be difficult to draw. Compare T3Preiser v. RodriguezK, 411 U.S. 475 (1973), with T3Clutchette v. ProcunierK, 497 F.2d 809 (9th Cir. 1974), modified, 510 F.2d 613 (1975).

