I74Advisory Committee Note

I21Under these rules the application for relief is in the form of a motion rather than a petition (see rule 1 and advisory committee note). Therefore, there is no requirement that the movant name a respondent. This is consistent with 28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2255. The United States Attorney for the district in which the judgment under attack was entered is the proper party to oppose the motion since the federal government is the movant's adversary of record.

I21If the movant is attacking a federal judgment which will subject him to future custody, he must be in present custody (see rule 1 and advisory committee note) as the result of a state or federal governmental action. He need not alter the nature of the motion by trying to include the government officer who presently has official custody of him as a psuedo-respondent, or third-party plaintiff, or other fabrication. The court hearing his motion attacking the future custody can exercise jurisdiction over those having him in present custody without the use of artificial pleading devices.

I21There is presently a split among the courts as to whether a person currently in state custody may use a ÿ1A2255 motion to obtain relief from a federal judgment under which he will be subjected to custody in the future. Negative, see T3Newton v. United StatesK, 329 F.Supp. 90 (S.D. Texas 1971); affirmative, see T3Desmond v. The United States Board of ParoleK, 397 F.2d 386 (1st Cir. 1968), cert. denied, 393 U.S. 919 (1968); and T3Paalino v. United StatesK, 314 F.Supp. 875 (C.D.Cal. 1970). It is intended that these rules settle the matter in favor of the prisoner's being able to file a ÿ1A2255 motion for relief under those circumstances. The proper district in which to file such a motion is the one in which is situated the court which rendered the sentence under attack.

I21Under rule 35, Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure, the court may correct an illegal sentence or a sentence imposed in an illegal manner, or may reduce the sentence. This remedy should be used, rather than a motion under these ÿ1A2255 rules, whenever applicable, but there is some overlap between the two proceedings which has caused the courts difficulty.

I21The movant should not be barred from an appropriate remedy because he has misstyled his motion. See T3United States v. MorganK, 346 U.S. 502, 505 (1954). The court should construe it as whichever one is proper under the circumstances and decide it on its merits. For a ÿ1A2255 motion construed as a rule 35 motion, see T3Heflin v. United StatesK, 358 U.S. 415 (1959); and T3United States v. CokeK, 404 F.2d 836 (2d Cir. 1968). For writ of error coram nobis treated as a rule 35 motion, see T3Hawkins v. United StatesK, 324 F.Supp. 223 (E.D.Texas, Tyler Division 1971). For a rule 35 motion treated as a ÿ1A2255 motion, see T3Moss v. United StatesK, 263 F.2d 615 (5th Cir. 1959); T3Jones v. United StatesK, 400 F.2d 892 (8th Cir. 1968), cert. denied 394 U.S. 991 (1969); and T3United States v. BrownK, 413 F.2d 878 (9th Cir. 1969), cert. denied, 397 U.S. 947 (1970).

I21One area of difference between ÿ1A2255 and rule 35 motions is that for the latter there is no requirement that the movant be ``in custody.'' T3Heflin v. United StatesK, 358 U.S. 415, 418, 422 (1959); T3Duggins v. United StatesK, 240 F.2d 479, 483 (6th Cir. 1957). Compare with rule 1 and advisory committee note for ÿ1A2255 motions. The importance of this distinction has decreased since T3Peyton v. RoweK, 391 U.S. 54 (1968), but it might still make a difference in particular situations.

I21A rule 35 motion is used to attack the sentence imposed, not the basis for the sentence. The court in T3Gilinsky v. United StatesK, 335 F.2d 914, 916 (9th Cir. 1964), stated, ``a Rule 35 motion presupposes a valid conviction. *** [C]ollateral attack on errors allegedly committed at trial is not permissible under Rule 35.'' By illustration the court noted at page 917: ``a Rule 35 proceeding contemplates the correction of a sentence of a court having jurisdiction. *** [J]urisdictional defects *** involve a collateral attack, they must ordinarily be presented under 28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2255.'' In T3United States v. SemetK, 295 F.Supp. 1084 (E.D. Okla. 1968), the prisoner moved under rule 35 and ÿ1A2255 to invalidate the sentence he was serving on the grounds of his failure to understand the charge to which he pleaded guilty. The court said:

I22As regards Defendant's Motion under Rule 35, said Motion must be denied as its presupposes a valid conviction of the offense with which he was charged and may be used only to attack the sentence. It may not be used to examine errors occurring prior to the imposition of sentence.

I71295 F.Supp. at 1085

I33See also: T3Moss v. United StatesK, 263 F.2d at 616; T3Duggins v. United StatesK, 240 F. 2d at 484; T3Migdal v. United StatesK, 298 F.2d 513, 514 (9th Cir. 1961); T3Jones v. United StatesK, 400 F.2d at 894; T3United States v. CokeK, 404 F.2d at 847; and T3United States v. BrownK, 413 F.2d at 879.

I21A major difficulty in deciding whether rule 35 or ÿ1A2255 is the proper remedy is the uncertainty as to what is meant by an ``illegal sentence.'' The Supreme Court dealt with this issue in T3Hill v. United StatesK, 368 U.S. 424 (1962). The prisoner brought a ÿ1A2255 motion to vacate sentence on the ground that he had not been given a Fed.R.Crim. P. 32(a) opportunity to make a statement in his own behalf at the time of sentencing. The majority held this was not an error subject to collateral attack under ÿ1A2255. The five-member majority considered the motion as one brought pursuant to rule 35, but denied relief, stating:

I31[T]he narrow function of Rule 35 is to permit correction at any time of an illegal T3sentenceK, not to re-examine errors occurring at the trial or other proceedings prior to the imposition of sentence. The sentence in this case was not illegal. The punishment meted out was not in excess of that prescribed by the relevant statutes, multiple terms were not imposed for the same offense, nor were the terms of the sentence itself legally or constitutionally invalid in any other respect.

I71368 U.S. at 430

I33The four dissenters felt the majority definition of ``illegal'' was too narrow.

I31[Rule 35] provides for the correction of an ``illegal sentence'' without regard to the reasons why that sentence is illegal and contains not a single word to support the Court's conclusion that only a sentence illegal by reason of the punishment it imposes is ``illegal'' within the meaning of the Rule. I would have thought that a sentence imposed in an illegal manner_whether the amount or form of the punishment meted out constitutes an additional violation of law or not_would be recognized as an ``illegal sentence'' under any normal reading of the English language.

I71368 U.S. at 431ÿ09432

I33The 1966 amendment of rule 35 added language permitting correction of a sentence imposed in an ``illegal manner.'' However, there is a 120-day time limit on a motion to do this, and the added language does not clarify the intent of the rule or its relation to ÿ1A2255.

I21The courts have been flexible in considering motions under circumstances in which relief might appear to be precluded by T3Hill v. United StatesK. In T3Peterson v. United StatesK, 432 F.2d 545 (8th Cir. 1970), the court was confronted with a motion for reduction of sentence by a prisoner claiming to have received a harsher sentence than his codefendants because he stood trial rather than plead guilty. He alleged that this violated his constitutional right to a jury trial. The court ruled that, even though it was past the 120-day time period for a motion to reduce sentence, the claim was still cognizable under rule 35 as a motion to correct an illegal sentence.

I21The courts have made even greater use of ÿ1A2255 in these types of situations. In T3United States v. LewisK, 392 F.2d 440 (4th Cir. 1968), the prisoner moved under ÿ1A2255 and rule 35 for relief from a sentence he claimed was the result of the judge's misunderstanding of the relevant sentencing law. The court held that he could not get relief under rule 35 because it was past the 120 days for correction of a sentence imposed in an illegal manner and under T3Hill v. United StatesK it was not an illegal sentence. However, ÿ1A2255 was applicable because of its ``otherwise subject to collateral attack'' language. The flaw was not a mere trial error relating to the finding of guilt, but a rare and unusual error which amounted to ``exceptional circumstances'' embraced in ÿ1A2255's words ``collateral attack.'' See 368 U.S. at 444 for discussion of other cases allowing use of ÿ1A2255 to attack the sentence itself in similar circumstances, especially where the judge has sentenced out of a misapprehension of the law.

I21In T3United States v. McCarthyK, 433 F.2d 591, 592 (1st Cir. 1970), the court allowed a prisoner who was past the time limit for a proper rule 35 motion to use ÿ1A2255 to attack the sentence which he received upon a plea of guilty on the ground that it was induced by an unfulfilled promise of the prosecutor to recommend leniency. The court specifically noted that under ÿ1A2255 this was a proper collateral attack on the sentence and there was no need to attack the conviction as well.

I21The court in T3United States v. MalcolmK, 432 F.2d 809, 814, 818 (2d Cir. 1970), allowed a prisoner to challenge his sentence under ÿ1A2255 without attacking the conviction. It held rule 35 inapplicable because the sentence was not illegal on its face, but the manner in which the sentence was imposed raised a question of the denial of due process in the sentencing itself which was cognizable under ÿ1A2255.

