I81Rule 9. Second or Successive Motions

I11Before presenting a second or successive motion, the moving party must obtain an order from the appropriate court of appeals authorizing the district court to consider the motion, as required by 28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2255, para. 8.

I53(As amended Pub. L. 94ÿ09426, ÿ1A2(9), (10), Sept. 28, 1976, 90 Stat. 1335; Apr. 26, 2004, eff. Dec. 1, 2004.)

I74Advisory Committee Note

I21Unlike the statutory provisions on habeas corpus (28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2241ÿ092254), ÿ1A2255 specifically provides that ``a motion for such relief may be made T3at any time.''K [Emphasis added.] Subdivision (a) provides that delayed motions may be barred from consideration if the government has been prejudiced in its ability to respond to the motion by the delay and the movant's failure to seek relief earlier is not excusable within the terms of the rule. Case law, dealing with this issue, is in conflict.

I21Some courts have held that the literal language of ÿ1A2255 precludes any possible time bar to a motion brought under it. In T3Heflin v. United StatesK, 358 U.S. 415 (1959), the concurring opinion noted:

I31The statute [28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2255] further provides; ``A motion *** may be made at any time.'' This *** simply means that, as in habeas corpus, there is no statute of limitations, no T3res judicataK, and that the doctrine of laches is inapplicable.

I71358 U.S. at 420

I33T3McKinney v. United StatesK, 208 F.2d 844 (D.C.Cir. 1953) reversed the district court's dismissal of a ÿ1A2255 motion for being too late, the court stating:

I22McKinney's present application for relief comes late in the day: he has served some fifteen years in prison. But tardiness is irrelevant where a constitutional issue is raised and where the prisoner is still confined.

I71208 F.2d at 846, 847

I33In accord, see: T3Juelich v. United StatesK, 300 F.2d 381, 383 (5th Cir. 1962); T3Conners v. United StatesK, 431 F.2d 1207, 1208 (9th Cir. 1970); T3Sturrup v. United StatesK, 218 F.Supp. 279, 281 (E.D.N.Car. 1963); and T3Banks v. United StatesK, 319 F.Supp. 649, 652 (S.D.N.Y. 1970).

I21It has also been held that delay in filing a ÿ1A2255 motion does not bar the movant because of lack of reasonable diligence in pressing the claim.

I31The statute [28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2255], when it states that the motion may be made at any time, excludes the addition of a showing of diligence in delayed filings. A number of courts have considered contentions similar to those made here and have concluded that there are no time limitations. This result excludes the requirement of diligence which is in reality a time limitation.

I71T3Haier v. United StatesK, 334 F.2d 441, 442 (10th Cir. 1964)

I21Other courts have recognized that delay may have a negative effect on the movant. In T3Raines v. United StatesK, 423 F.2d 526 (4th Cir. 1970), the court stated:

I31[B]oth petitioners' silence for extended periods, one for 28 months and the other for nine years, serves to render their allegations less believable. ``Although a delay in filing a section 2255 motion is not a controlling element *** it may merit some consideration ***.''

I71423 F.2d at 531

I21In T3Aiken v. United StatesK, 191 F.Supp. 43, 50 (M.D.N.Car. 1961), aff'd 296 F.2d 604 (4th Cir. 1961), the court said: ``While motions under 28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2255 may be made at any time, the lapse of time affects the good faith and credibility of the moving party.'' For similar conclusions, see: T3Parker v. United StatesK, 358 F.2d 50, 54 n. 4 (7th Cir. 1965), cert. denied, 386 U.S. 916 (1967); T3Le Clair v. United StatesK, 241 F.Supp. 819, 824 (N.D. Ind. 1965); T3Malone v. United StatesK, 299 F.2d 254, 256 (6th Cir. 1962), cert. denied, 371 U.S. 863 (1962); T3Howell v. United StatesK, 442 F.2d 265, 274 (7th Cir. 1971); and T3United States v. WigginsK, 184 F. Supp. 673, 676 (D.C.Cir. 1960).

I21There have been holdings by some courts that a delay in filing a ÿ1A2255 motion operates to increase the burden of proof which the movant must meet to obtain relief. The reasons for this, as expressed in T3United States v. BosticK, 206 F.Supp. 855 (D.C.Cir. 1962), are equitable in nature.

I22Obviously, the burden of proof on a motion to vacate a sentence under 28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2255 is on the moving party. ... The burden is particularly heavy if the issue is one of fact and a long time has elapsed since the trial of the case. While neither the statute of limitations nor laches can bar the assertion of a constitutional right, nevertheless, the passage of time may make it impracticable to retry a case if the motion is granted and a new trial is ordered. No doubt, at times such a motion is a product of an afterthought. Long delay may raise a question of good faith.

I71206 F.Supp. at 856ÿ09857

I33See also T3United States v. WigginsK, 184 F.Supp. at 676.

I21A requirement that the movant display reasonable diligence in filing a ÿ1A2255 motion has been adopted by some courts dealing with delayed motions. The court in T3United States v. MooreK, 166 F.2d 102 (7th Cir. 1948), cert. denied, 334 U.S. 849 (1948), did this, again for equitable reasons.

I22[W]e agree with the District Court that the petitioner has too long slept upon his rights. *** [A]pparently there is no limitation of time within which *** a motion to vacate may be filed, except that an applicant must show reasonable diligence in presenting his claim. ***

I22The reasons which support the rule requiring diligence seem obvious. *** Law enforcement officials change, witnesses die, memories grow dim. The prosecuting tribunal is put to a disadvantage if an unexpected retrial should be necessary after long passage of time.

I71166 F.2d at 105

I33In accord see T3Desmond v. United StatesK, 333 F.2d 378, 381 (1st Cir. 1964), on remand, 345 F.2d 225 (1st Cir. 1965).

I21One of the major arguments advanced by the courts which would penalize a movant who waits an unduly long time before filing a ÿ1A2255 motion is that such delay is highly prejudicial to the prosecution. In T3Desmond v. United StatesK, writing of a ÿ1A2255 motion alleging denial of effective appeal because of deception by movant's own counsel, the court said:

I31[A]pplications for relief such as this must be made promptly. It will not do for a prisoner to wait until government witnesses have become unavailable as by death, serious illness or absence from the country, or until the memory of available government witnesses has faded. It will not even do for a prisoner to wait any longer than is reasonably necessary to prepare appropriate moving papers, however inartistic, after discovery of the deception practiced upon him by his attorney.

I71333 F.2d at 381

I33In a similar vein are T3United States v. MooreK and T3United States v. BosticK, supra, and T3United States v. WigginsK, 184 F. Supp. at 676.

I21Subdivision (a) provides a flexible, equitable time limitation based on laches to prevent movants from withholding their claims so as to prejudice the government both in meeting the allegations of the motion and in any possible retrial. It includes a reasonable diligence requirement for ascertaining possible grounds for relief. If the delay is found to be excusable, or nonprejudicial to the government, the time bar is inoperative.

I21Subdivision (b) is consistent with the language of ÿ1A2255 and relevant case law.

I21The annexed form is intended to serve the same purpose as the comparable one included in the ÿ1A2254 rules.

I21For further discussion applicable to this rule, see the advisory committee note to rule 9 of the ÿ1A2254 rules.

