I81Rule 11. Certificate of Appealability; Time to Appeal

I11(a) T4Certificate of AppealabilityK. The district court must issue or deny a certificate of appealability when it enters a final order adverse to the applicant. Before entering the final order, the court may direct the parties to submit arguments on whether a certificate should issue. If the court issues a certificate, the court must state the specific issue or issues that satisfy the showing required by 28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2253(c)(2). If the court denies a certificate, a party may not appeal the denial but may seek a certificate from the court of appeals under Federal Rule of Appellate Procedure 22. A motion to reconsider a denial does not extend the time to appeal.

I11(b) T4Time to AppealK. Federal Rule of Appellate Procedure 4(a) governs the time to appeal an order entered under these rules. A timely notice of appeal must be filed even if the district court issues a certificate of appealability. These rules do not extend the time to appeal the original judgment of conviction.

I53(As amended Apr. 30, 1979, eff. Aug. 1, 1979; Apr. 26, 2004, eff. Dec. 1, 2004; Mar. 26, 2009, eff. Dec. 1, 2009.)

I74Advisory Committee Note

I21Rule 11 is intended to make clear that, although a ÿ1A2255 action is a continuation of the criminal case, the bringing of a ÿ1A2255 action does not extend the time.

I711979 T4Amendment

I21Prior to the promulgation of the Rules Governing Section 2255 Proceedings, the courts consistently held that the time for appeal in a section 2255 case is as provided in Fed.R.App.P. 4(a), that is, 60 days when the government is a party, rather than as provided in appellate rule 4(b), which says that the time is 10 days in criminal cases. This result has often been explained on the ground that rule 4(a) has to do with civil cases and that ``proceedings under section 2255 are civil in nature.'' E.g., T3Rothman v. United StatesK, 508 F.2d 648 (3d Cir. 1975). Because the new section 2255 rules are based upon the premise ``that a motion under ÿ1A2255 is a further step in the movant's criminal case rather than a separate civil action,'' see Advisory Committee Note to rule 1, the question has arisen whether the new rules have the effect of shortening the time for appeal to that provided in appellate rule 4(b). A sentence has been added to rule 11 in order to make it clear that this is not the case.

I21Even though section 2255 proceedings are a further step in the criminal case, the added sentence correctly states current law. In T3United States v. HaymanK, 342 U.S. 205 (1952), the Supreme Court noted that such appeals ``are governed by the civil rules applicable to appeals from final judgments in habeas corpus actions.'' In support, the Court cited T3Mercado v. United StatesK, 183 F.2d 486 (1st Cir. 1950), a case rejecting the argument that because ÿ1A2255 proceedings are criminal in nature the time for appeal is only 10 days. The T3MercadoK court concluded that the situation was governed by that part of 28 U.S.C. ÿ1A2255 which reads: ``An appeal may be taken to the court of appeals from the order entered on the motion as from a final judgment on application for a writ of habeas corpus.'' Thus, because appellate rule 4(a) is applicable in habeas cases, it likewise governs in ÿ1A2255 cases even though they are criminal in nature.

