I89. Application for warrant

I11A United States attorney or assistant United States attorney or a person authorized by the Attorney General_

I12(1) upon his own affidavit or that of another credible person, stating the existence of either of the grounds of attachments enumerated in section 2710 of this title and

I12(2) upon production of legal evidence of the debt

Q04

I10may apply for a warrant of attachment to a judge, or, in his absence, to the clerk of any court of the United States having original jurisdiction of the cause of action.

I53(Added Pub. L. 86ÿ09682, ÿ1A9, Sept. 2, 1960, 74 Stat. 707.)

I76Codification

I21Section was derived from R.S. ÿ1A925, which was originally classified to section 738 of former Title 28. Following the general revision and enactment of Title 28 by act June 25, 1948, R.S. ÿ1A925 was reclassified to section 838 of Title 39. R.S. ÿ1A925 was repealed by section 12(c) of Pub. L. 86ÿ09682 (section 1 of which revised and enacted Title 39), and reenacted by section 9 thereof as section 2711 of this title.

I80ÿ1A2712

I89. Issue of warrant

I11Upon an order of a judge of a court, or, in his absence and upon the clerk's own initiative, the clerk shall issue a warrant for the attachment of the property belonging to the person specified in the affidavit. The marshal shall execute the warrant forthwith and take the property attached, if personal, in his custody, subject to the interlocutory or final orders of the court.

I53(Added Pub. L. 86ÿ09682, ÿ1A9, Sept. 2, 1960, 74 Stat. 707.)

I76Codification

I21Section was derived from R.S. ÿ1A926, which was originally classified to section 739 of former Title 28. Following the general revision and enactment of Title 28 by act June 25, 1948, R.S. ÿ1A926 was reclassified to section 839 of Title 39. R.S. ÿ1A926 was repealed by section 12(c) of Pub. L. 86ÿ09682 (section 1 of which revised and enacted Title 39), and reenacted by section 9 thereof as section 2712 of this title.

I80ÿ1A2713

I89. Trial of ownership of property

I11Not later than twenty days before the return day of a warrant issued under section 2712 of this title, the party whose property is attached, on notice to the United States Attorney, may file a plea in abatement, denying the allegations of the affidavit, or denying ownership in the defendant of the property attached. The court, upon application of either party, shall order a trial by jury of the issues. Where the parties, by consent, waive a trial by jury, the court shall decide the issues. A party claiming ownership of the property attached and seeking its return is limited to the remedy afforded by this section, but his right to an action of trespass, or other action for damages, is not impaired.

I53(Added Pub. L. 86ÿ09682, ÿ1A9, Sept. 2, 1960, 74 Stat. 707.)

I76Codification

I21Section was derived from R.S. ÿ1A927, which was originally classified to section 740 of former Title 28. Following the general revision and enactment of Title 28 by act June 25, 1948, R.S. ÿ1A927 was reclassified to section 840 of Title 39. R.S. ÿ1A927 was repealed by section 12(c) of Pub. L. 86ÿ09682 (section 1 of which revised and enacted Title 39), and reenacted by section 9 thereof as section 2713 of this title.

I80ÿ1A2714

I89. Investment of proceeds of attached property

I11When the property attached is sold on an interlocutory order or is producing revenue, the money arising from the sale or revenue shall be invested, under the order of the court, in securities of the United States. The accretions therefrom are subject to the order of the court.

I53(Added Pub. L. 86ÿ09682, ÿ1A9, Sept. 2, 1960, 74 Stat. 707.)

