I11(d) T4AssetsK._For purposes of this section, assets do not include property that is transferred, concealed, or removed with intent to hinder, delay, or defraud creditors or that has been transferred in a manner making the transfer voidable under this subchapter.

I11(e) T4DebtsK._For purposes of this section, debts do not include an obligation to the extent such obligation is secured by a valid lien on property of the debtor not included as an asset.

I53(Added Pub. L. 101ÿ09647, title XXXVI, ÿ1A3611, Nov. 29, 1990, 104 Stat. 4961.)

I80ÿ1A3303

I89. Value for transfer or obligation

I11(a) T4TransactionK._Value is given for a transfer or an obligation if, in exchange for the transfer or obligation, property is transferred or an antecedent debt is secured or satisfied, but value does not include an unperformed promise made otherwise than in the ordinary course of the promisor's business to furnish support to the debtor or another person.

I11(b) T4Reasonably Equivalent ValueK._For the purposes of sections 3304 and 3307, a person gives a reasonably equivalent value if the person acquires an interest of the debtor in an asset pursuant to a regularly conducted, noncollusive foreclosure sale or execution of a power of sale for the acquisition or disposition of such interest upon default under a mortgage, deed of trust, or security agreement.

I11(c) T4Present ValueK._A transfer is made for present value if the exchange between the debtor and the transferee is intended by them to be contemporaneous and is in fact substantially contemporaneous.

I53(Added Pub. L. 101ÿ09647, title XXXVI, ÿ1A3611, Nov. 29, 1990, 104 Stat. 4961.)

I80ÿ1A3304

I89. Transfer fraudulent as to a debt to the United States

I11(a) T4Debt Arising Before TransferK._Except as provided in section 3307, a transfer made or obligation incurred by a debtor is fraudulent as to a debt to the United States which arises before the transfer is made or the obligation is incurred if_

I12(1)(A) the debtor makes the transfer or incurs the obligation without receiving a reasonably equivalent value in exchange for the transfer or obligation; and

I12(B) the debtor is insolvent at that time or the debtor becomes insolvent as a result of the transfer or obligation; or

I12(2)(A) the transfer was made to an insider for an antecedent debt, the debtor was insolvent at the time; and

I12(B) the insider had reasonable cause to believe that the debtor was insolvent.

Q04

I11(b) T4Transfers Without Regard to Date of JudgmentK._(1) Except as provided in section 3307, a transfer made or obligation incurred by a debtor is fraudulent as to a debt to the United States, whether such debt arises before or after the transfer is made or the obligation is incurred, if the debtor makes the transfer or incurs the obligation_

I12(A) with actual intent to hinder, delay, or defraud a creditor; or

I12(B) without receiving a reasonably equivalent value in exchange for the transfer or obligation if the debtor_

I13(i) was engaged or was about to engage in a business or a transaction for which the remaining assets of the debtor were unreasonably small in relation to the business or transaction; or

I13(ii) intended to incur, or believed or reasonably should have believed that he would incur, debts beyond his ability to pay as they became due.

Q04

I11(2) In determining actual intent under paragraph (1), consideration may be given, among other factors, to whether_

I12(A) the transfer or obligation was to an insider;

I12(B) the debtor retained possession or control of the property transferred after the transfer;

I12(C) the transfer or obligation was disclosed or concealed;

I12(D) before the transfer was made or obligation was incurred, the debtor had been sued or threatened with suit;

I12(E) the transfer was of substantially all the debtor's assets;

I12(F) the debtor absconded;

I12(G) the debtor removed or concealed assets;

I12(H) the value of the consideration received by the debtor was reasonably equivalent to the value of the asset transferred or the amount of the obligation incurred;

I12(I) the debtor was insolvent or became insolvent shortly after the transfer was made or the obligation was incurred;

I12(J) the transfer occurred shortly before or shortly after a substantial debt was incurred; and

I12(K) the debtor transferred the essential assets of the business to a lienor who transferred the assets to an insider of the debtor.

I53(Added Pub. L. 101ÿ09647, title XXXVI, ÿ1A3611, Nov. 29, 1990, 104 Stat. 4961.)

I80ÿ1A3305

I89. When transfer is made or obligation is incurred

I11For the purposes of this subchapter:

I12(1) A transfer is made_

I13(A) with respect to an asset that is real property (other than a fixture, but including the interest of a seller or purchaser under a contract for the sale of the asset), when the transfer is so far perfected that a good-faith purchaser of the asset from the debtor against whom applicable law permits the transfer to be perfected cannot acquire an interest in the asset that is superior to the interest of the transferee; and

I13(B) with respect to an asset that is not real property or that is a fixture, when the transfer is so far perfected that a creditor on a simple contract cannot acquire, otherwise than under this subchapter, a judicial lien that is superior to the interest of the transferee.

Q04

I12(2) If applicable law permits the transfer to be perfected as approved in paragraph (1) and the transfer is not so perfected before the commencement of an action or proceeding for relief under this subchapter, the transfer is deemed made immediately before the commencement of the action or proceeding.

I12(3) If applicable law does not permit the transfer to be perfected as provided in paragraph (1), the transfer is made when it becomes effective between the debtor and the transferee.

I12(4) A transfer is not made until the debtor has acquired rights in the asset transferred.

I12(5) An obligation is incurred_

I13(A) if oral, when it becomes effective between the parties; or

I13(B) if evidenced by a writing executed by the obligor, when such writing is delivered to or for the benefit of the obligee.

I53(Added Pub. L. 101ÿ09647, title XXXVI, ÿ1A3611, Nov. 29, 1990, 104 Stat. 4962.)

I80ÿ1A3306

I89. Remedies of the United States

I11(a) T4In GeneralK._In an action or proceeding under this subchapter for relief against a transfer or obligation, the United States, subject to section 3307 and to applicable principles of equity and in accordance with the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, may obtain_

I12(1) avoidance of the transfer or obligation to the extent necessary to satisfy the debt to the United States;

I12(2) a remedy under this chapter against the asset transferred or other property of the transferee; or

I12(3) any other relief the circumstances may require.

Q04

I11(b) T4LimitationK._A claim for relief with respect to a fraudulent transfer or obligation under this subchapter is extinguished unless action is brought_

I12(1) under section 3304(b)(1)(A) within 6 years after the transfer was made or the obligation was incurred or, if later, within 2 years after the transfer or obligation was or could reasonably have been discovered by the claimant;

I12(2) under subsection (a)(1) or (b)(1)(B) of section 3304 within 6 years after the transfer was made or the obligation was incurred; or

I12(3) under section 3304(a)(2) within 2 years after the transfer was made or the obligation was incurred.

I53(Added Pub. L. 101ÿ09647, title XXXVI, ÿ1A3611, Nov. 29, 1990, 104 Stat. 4963.)

